	"notes": [
		{
			"id": "nCPIKEG2qcEStGeRe",
			"markdown": "The Medic keeps people alive. Whether you are patching up gunshot wounds in a back-alley clinic, stabilizing casualties under fire, fighting a planetary plague, installing cybernetics, or trying to understand the anatomy of something that evolved beneath a methane ocean, you solve problems no one else can. In many campaigns, the Medic is the difference between a temporary setback and a dead character.\n\nNot every Medic is a hospital doctor. Some are trauma surgeons, military corpsmen, toxicologists, cybernetic engineers, psychologists, coroners, veterinarians, or disease-control specialists. Others are frontier physicians working without support, supplies, or legal protection. In high-tech settings, Medics may deal with cloned organs, synthetic pharmaceuticals, neural augmentation, alien biology, and industrial contaminants as often as ordinary injuries.\n\nThe *Field Medic* specializes in emergency care under dangerous conditions where hesitation can kill. Military corpsmen, disaster-response personnel, combat paramedics, wilderness rescue workers, and expedition doctors all fit this archetype. Field Medics thrive in unstable environments where treatment must happen immediately and often under fire. They emphasize Diagnosis, Physician, Survival, Scrounging, Observation, Guns, Wrestling, Combat Reflexes, Fearlessness, Fit, and High Manual Dexterity. Common disadvantages include Sense of Duty, Charitable, Pacifism (Cannot Harm Innocents), Combat Paralysis, Workaholic, or Vow (Never Refuse Medical Aid).\n\nThe *Surgeon* focuses on advanced procedures, invasive treatment, and medical technology. Surgeons include trauma specialists, cyberdocs, augmentation engineers, transplant experts, and elite hospital physicians. In high-tech or transhuman settings, they may install cybernetics, cloned organs, or neural interfaces as often as they repair ordinary injuries. Surgeons prioritize Surgery, Diagnosis, Electronics Operation (Medical), Research, Bioengineering, High Manual Dexterity, Eidetic Memory, Single-Minded, and Versatile. Typical disadvantages include Overconfidence, Workaholic, Obsession, Delusion (“I’m God when I’m your doctor!”), Stubbornness, or Truthfulness.\n\nThe *Hazard Medic* deals with disease, toxins, contamination, and hostile environments where biology itself becomes the enemy. Outbreak investigators, toxicologists, quarantine officers, industrial safety specialists, and biochemical emergency teams belong to this archetype. Hazard Medics excel in plague campaigns, industrial disasters, hostile colony worlds, and survival horror settings involving contamination or engineered pathogens. They focus on Hazardous Materials, Poisons, Expert Skill (Epidemiology), Pharmacy, Vacc Suit, Chemistry, Fearlessness, Resistant, Intuition, and Less Sleep. Common disadvantages include Curious, Nightmares, Paranoia, Workaholic, Sense of Duty, or Pacifism (Cannot Kill).\n\nThe *Xenomedic* studies unfamiliar lifeforms and nonhuman biology. Xenomedics may serve as alien veterinarians, first-contact physicians, exobiologists, or specialists assigned to multicultural colonies and exploration vessels. They must navigate not only strange anatomies, but also unfamiliar customs, ecosystems, and ethical assumptions. This archetype emphasizes Physiology (Alien Species), Biology, Diagnosis, Naturalist, Veterinary, Survival, Cultural Adaptability, Intuition, Languages, and Versatile. Typical disadvantages include Curious, Xenophilia, Sense of Duty, Charitable, Obsession, or Truthfulness.\n\nThe *Medical Investigator* blends medicine with deduction, forensic analysis, and psychological insight. Coroners, forensic psychiatrists, behavioral analysts, crime-scene specialists, and medical examiners all fit this archetype. Medical Investigators are especially valuable in conspiracy, horror, and investigative campaigns where understanding the victim is as important as understanding the crime. They focus on Forensics, Psychology, Diagnosis, Intelligence Analysis, Research, Observation, Intuition, Empathy, Eidetic Memory, and Sensitive. Common disadvantages include Guilt Complex, Obsession, Nightmares, Honesty, Pacifism (Cannot Harm Innocents), or Workaholic.\n\nMany Medics branch into related specialties depending on the needs of the campaign. Some become capable researchers, investigators, or survivalists, while others develop expertise with hazardous environments, alien ecosystems, or advanced technology. In dangerous settings, a Medic who can shoot straight, stay calm under pressure, and function independently is often far more valuable than one who only knows how to work inside a clean hospital."
		}
	]
}
